<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 11.2.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. The Competency in Detail</h3>
  <p>The following drop-downs contain information on each of the knowledge areas and skills needed to implement the competency. <strong>Please explore the content below.</strong></p>
  <h3>Systems Approach</h3>
  <p><strong>Knowledge Areas. </strong>MCH leaders will demonstrate a working knowledge of:</p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>11K1.</strong> How organizations or practice settings function as systems.</button>
  <div class="panel">
   
    <p>A system is an organized collection of parts that work together to accomplish an overall goal or outcome. It has inputs that are used to create certain outputs that jointly accomplish its overall goal. Ongoing feedback among a system&rsquo;s various parts makes certain they stay focused on accomplishing the overall goal.<sup>1</sup> </p>
    <p>Organizations and practice settings are systems. </p>
    <p>A logic model can be a useful tool to visualize the flow of activities into, through and out of a system to produce the desired outcomes of an organization:<sup>1</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Inputs to the system</strong>: these include people, money, equipment, facilities, supplies</li>
      <li><strong>Processes that occur to the inputs:</strong> the activities, strategies or methods that produce the results desired by the organization or program</li>
      <li><strong>Outputs from the processes:</strong> the tangible results of the major processes in the organization</li>
      <li><strong>Outcomes:</strong> the impacts on those people whom the organization wanted to benefit with its programs/efforts</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Within each organization are subsystems that are part of the larger system. These are usually the recurring processes within the organization, such as marketing and financial management. The outputs of one subsystem can be the inputs of another. <a href="https://managementhelp.org/systems/systems-of-management-functions.pdf">Here are some examples of common management systems.</a></p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-compass3"></i> <strong>11K2.</strong> Principles and concepts related to broader systems.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p><strong>The Principles of Systems Thinking</strong>. Systems thinking is an approach used by a variety of fields, including business, engineering, physics, military science, agriculture and weather forecasting.</p>
    <p>No single discipline defines systems thinking. However, there are some fundamental systems-thinking perspectives and approaches that are shared across fields:<sup>2</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Increased attention to how new knowledge is gained, managed, exchanged, interpreted, integrated and distributed</li>
      <li>Emphasis on a network-centric approach that encourages relationship-building among and between individuals and organizations across traditional disciplines and fields in order to achieve relevant goals and objectives</li>
      <li>The development of models and projections, using a variety of analytic approaches (e.g., differential equations, agent-based modeling, system-dynamics modeling) in order to improve strategic decision-making</li>
      <li>Systems organizing in order to foster improvements in organizational structures and functions</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Networks form the backbone of a system by harnessing the potential of linking various stakeholder individuals and groups. Being able to understand how networks form and are managed and how to use that understanding to build and maintain healthy networks are critical to functioning within a systems environment.<sup>2</sup></p>
    <p><strong>Features and Issues of Systems</strong>. These characteristics are shared by all systems:<sup>3</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>The parts of the system are interdependent (a change in the status of one causes change in others, sometimes after a time delay).</li>
      <li>All the parts are needed to produce the behavior of the system.</li>
      <li>The behavior of the system changes over time.</li>
      <li>The structure of the system generates its behavior.</li>
      <li>Causes often generate effects which then become causes.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Principles of Building Constituencies and Engaging in Collaborative Endeavors</strong>. Constituency development involves four practice elements:<sup>4,5</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Know the community, its constituents, and its capabilities: 
        <ul>
          <li index="0">Know a community's economics, demographics, norms, history, experience with engagement efforts, and perception of those initiating the engagement activities.</li>
        </ul>
        <ul>
          <li index="1">Recognize and respect the various backgrounds in a community and other factors that indicate its range of perspectives in all aspects of designing and implementing community engagement approaches.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Establish positions and strategies that guide interactions with constituents: 
        <ul>
          <li>Be clear about the population/communities to be engaged and the goals of the effort. </li>
          <li>Remember that community self-determination is the responsibility and right of all people who comprise a community. </li>
          <li>Be prepared to release control to the community, and be flexible enough to meet the changing needs of the community. </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Build and sustain formal and informal networks to maintain relationships, communicate messages, and leverage resources.
        <ul>
          <li>Identify and analyze network structures (communication, power, and resource flow).</li>
          <li>Affiliate with those in existing networks.</li>
          <li>Develop and deliver ongoing messages across formal and informal communication channels to maintain information flow and coordinated activity.</li>
          <li>Target communications and resources to leverage agenda-setting processes within a community.</li>
          <li>Establish, use, and monitor resource exchange systems that support network interactions and coordinated, collaborative community work.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Mobilize communities and constituencies for decision-making and social action.
        <ul>
          <li>Move communities through the process of dialogue, debate, and decision-making to obtain commitment to a collaborative goal.</li>
          <li>Determine who will do what and how it will be done.</li>
          <li>Implement activities.</li>
          <li>Monitor, evaluate, adjust and reevaluate activities in a cyclical fashion.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Concepts of Implementation Science</strong>. Implementation science is the scientific study of the use of strategies to adopt and integrate evidence-based health interventions into clinical and community settings to improve patient outcomes and benefit population health. The field arose to address the time delay that exists between the discovery of effective interventions and their implementation in the practice setting &mdash; a delay reported to be on the order of 17 years.<sup>6</sup></p>
    <p>Implementation theories, models and frameworks are abundant. They share some common features.<sup>7</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Multiphase: There are discrete phases of work to consider when using an implementation framework. For example, the EPIS framework has four phases: Exploration, Preparation, Implementation and Sustainment.</li>
      <li>Multilevel: Many levels within a practice are affected by the implementation of an intervention, from the individual to the group or team they&rsquo;re working with, to the organization itself, and finally to the larger system and/or environment in which everything takes place.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Choosing a theory, model or framework to use depends largely on the outcomes being sought. Consider criteria in four broad categories: usability, testability, applicability, and acceptability.<sup>7</sup></p>
    <p>Applying implementation science frameworks and models has the potential to:<sup>8</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Reduce program costs</li>
      <li>Improve health outcomes</li>
      <li>Decrease health variations in a community</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Factors that Influence the Use of Research Findings in Practice</strong>. <p>A host of factors influence the use of research findings in practice. These include:<sup>9</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Political climate (e.g., policy mandates for the use of evidence-based practice)</li>
      <li>Organizational practices (is the organization research-receptive?)</li>
      <li>Presence and roles of intermediaries</li>
      <li>Individual characteristics (e.g., knowledge of and attitudes toward research)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Evidence from research is more likely to be used in policy and program development when the      following are in place:<sup>10</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Mechanisms to ensure ready access to research findings and summaries of research</li>
      <li>Frequent interaction between researchers and policy-makers</li>
      <li>Organizational readiness to use evidence from research</li>
      <li>Supportive resources and tools</li>
      <li>Mechanisms for the generation of new evidence from research that is highly relevant to the priorities of the agency and applicable to local circumstances</li></ul></div>
 
  <p><strong>Skills</strong></p>
  <p><strong><em>Foundational. </em></strong><em>At a foundational level, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-share"></i> <strong>11S1.</strong> Relate mission/vision/goals to broader system and advance advance responsiveness to community perspectives.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>An organization&rsquo;s mission, vision and goals all speak to its purpose.<sup>11</sup></p>
    <p>A mission statement presents the organization&rsquo;s reason for being, and how it serves its stakeholders. It may also include the organization&rsquo;s values, including those to advance various perspectives, balanced opportunities, welcoming participation, and usability. It answers the questions &ldquo;Who are we?&rdquo; and &ldquo;What do we value?&rdquo;</p>
    <p>An organization&rsquo;s vision statement is a forward-looking declaration of what it aspires to become as it pursues its purpose. Vision statements answer the question &ldquo;Where are we going as an organization?&rdquo;</p>
    <p>The mission and vision of an organization inform the development of a strategy that lays out how the organization will achieve its vision. Key to this strategy are goals and objectives. These measure the success or failure of the strategy.</p>
    <p>Understanding how the mission, vision and goals of an organization relate to the broader system in which it operates is key to working effectively and having a measurable impact on that system. </p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-chart"></i> <strong>11S2.</strong> Budgeting/resources efficiency,  problem-solving.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Knowing how to create and use a <strong>budget</strong> is an important skill for any leader, but it is especially important in MCH.<sup>12</sup></p>
    <p>Each MCH organization will have its own <a href="https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/finances/managing-finances/annual-budget/main">budget process and timeline</a>. It can be quarterly, annual, or even biannual.</p>
    <p>The budgeting process has its origins in <a href="https://www.naccho.org/programs/public-health-infrastructure/performance-improvement/strategic-planning">strategic planning</a>. An organization&rsquo;s strategic plan informs its business plan. This allows the organization to begin to implement the strategies that are part of that plan, and to develop and execute a budget. </p>
    <p>As a part of budget development, MCH leaders should take a look at an organization&rsquo;s goals and objectives, informed by its financial statements, such as income statements, balance sheets, and cash-flow statements.<sup>12</sup> These reveal whether an organization is on track or not in a given year. Effective resource use, control of standards, and coordination of tasks within an organization will allow it to achieve its goals and objectives within a certain budget.</p>
    <p>The process of developing a new budget should focus on the financial events that shaped the previous budget period. </p>
    <p>At the conclusion of a fiscal year, it&rsquo;s generally required that a nonprofit organization hire a CPA to <a href="https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/finances/managing-finances/finance-committee/main">audit</a> the previous year&rsquo;s activities using financial statements and other information to determine whether appropriate accounting practices were used throughout the year.<sup>13</sup></p>
    <p>The audit process provides an opportunity to identify activities that did not yield the expected performance. Leadership should apply <strong>problem-solving skills </strong>to resolve these issues separately from the budget-development process.</p>
    <p>Here is one potential approach to problem-solving:<sup>14</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Make a list of the top problems. </li>
      <li>For each current problem, spend time considering its root causes. 
        <ul>
          <li>Ask yourself and your colleagues and staff, &ldquo;Why is this a problem now?&rdquo;</li>
          <li>Take each of those identified causes and ask again, &ldquo;Why is this a problem?&rdquo;</li>
          <li>Ask this question repeatedly until you identify the root causes of a problem. </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Take these root causes and quickly generate a list of possible solutions. </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Taking action to address root causes is more effective than working to address the symptoms of the problem, but it takes intention. In crisis-mode, symptoms call for attention. You likely will have to restructure some programs, but keep a flexible mindset.<sup>14</sup></p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-list-alt"></i> <strong>11S3.</strong> Develop projects reflecting a broader systems approach.</button>
  <div class="panel">
	  <p>Developing Projects with a Broader Systems Approach</p>
<p>A systems approach to project development involves considering the interconnectedness of components within a system and how they interact with the external environment. This holistic perspective leads to more sustainable, effective, and resilient projects.
	  <p>Key Steps to a Systems Approach</p>
<ul><li><strong>Define the System:</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Clearly identify the boundaries of the system. What components are included, and where do external influences start?</li>
    <li>Understand the core functions of the system and its purpose.</li>
    <li>Analyze the system's environment and its interactions with other systems.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Identify Stakeholders:</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Determine who is affected by or has an interest in the project.</li>
    <li>Understand the needs, expectations, and potential impacts on each stakeholder group.</li>
    <li>Develop strategies to engage stakeholders throughout the project lifecycle.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Map Interdependencies:</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Identify the relationships between different components within the system.</li>
    <li>Understand how changes in one part of the system affect other parts.</li>
    <li>Visualize interconnections using diagrams or models (e.g., system dynamics, causal loop diagrams).</li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li><strong>Consider Feedback Loops:</strong>
<ul>
  <li>In a feedback loop the outputs of a system are circled back and used as inputs; these can either positive or negative. Analyze how outputs from the system can influence inputs and processes.</li>
   <li>Identify potential reinforcing or balancing feedback loops.</li>
   <li>Develop strategies to manage feedback loops effectively.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Assess Impacts:</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Evaluate the potential environmental, social, and economic impacts of the project.</li>
    <li>Consider both short-term and long-term consequences.</li>
    <li>Develop mitigation strategies for negative impacts and enhance positive outcomes.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Set Clear Objectives:</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Define specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, and time-bound (SMART) objectives.</li>
    <li>Align objectives with the overall system goals.</li>
    <li>Ensure objectives consider the needs of various stakeholders.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Develop Robust Solutions:</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Explore multiple options and consider their impact on the entire system.</li>
    <li>Select solutions that are adaptable and resilient to change.</li>
    <li>Design solutions that promote sustainability and long-term viability.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Implement with a Systems Perspective:</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Integrate systems thinking into project management processes.</li>
    <li>Monitor system performance and adjust as needed.</li>
    <li>Foster collaboration and communication among project teams and stakeholders.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Evaluate and Learn:</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Assess the project’s outcomes against the system's objectives.</li>
    <li>Identify lessons learned and apply them to future projects.
    </li>
    <li>Continuously improve the system through feedback and adaptation.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
    <p><strong>How to Develop Effective Meeting Agendas</strong></p> 
	  <p>Effective meeting agendas are the key to effective meetings. Here are several characteristics of effective agendas:<sup>15</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>They reflect the needs of team members: Ask for agenda items from team members prior to the meeting.</li>
      <li>Discuss interdependent issues that affect the entire team: Use meeting time to focus on topics and decisions that affect everyone and require input from all.</li>
      <li>Denote whether an agenda item will require team members to listen and gather new information, provide input on something that needs to be decided, or require a decision be made.</li>
      <li>Phrase agenda items that require decisions as questions: Team members will then know what they&rsquo;ll be working to resolve.</li>
      <li>Suggest a process for addressing each agenda item: This can help keep the discussion organized and productive for all team members.</li>
      <li>Estimate a realistic amount of time for each agenda item: In doing this, you may realize your agenda is too long for your allotted meeting time.</li>
      <li>Specify how team members should prepare for the meeting, including whether individuals should prepare to lead discussions or provide information on specific agenda items: This usually requires having the agenda prepared well enough in advance of the meeting that staffers can get ready.</li>
      <li>At the start of each meeting, ask whether anyone has an issue that will affect the stated meeting agenda.</li>
      <li>At the conclusion of each meeting, conduct a quick evaluation of the meeting process by asking what went well, and what should be done differently at the next meeting. Incorporate feedback into the next meeting&rsquo;s agenda.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>How to Lead Meetings Effectively</strong></p> <p>Meetings are necessary for teams to be effective. Though many dread meetings, they can be catalysts for a lot of your work. Here are tips for leading effective meetings:<sup>16</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Prepare for each meeting: Create an agenda and distribute it and supporting materials to attendees in a timely manner.</li>
      <li>Consider who should attend carefully: Only invite people to attend who should be there</li>
      <li>Start and end on time: Meetings should rarely last longer than an hour.</li>
      <li>Keep the meeting moving and in control: Do not let one person hijack the meeting with their own agenda or talk over everyone else.</li>
      <li>Ensure participants are using technology to engage in meeting activities: Share a Google Doc or similar with participants if necessary to capture group input.</li>
      <li>Familiarize yourself with meeting software prior to the meeting.</li>
      <li>Follow up with participants immediately: Assign action items from the meeting and distribute minutes.    </li>
    </ul>
	  <p><strong>How to Lead Teams Effectively</strong>.</p> <p>Ideas for how to effectively lead teams abound. Here are a few selected pointers for team leaders.<sup>17</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Have mutual trust and respect for your team members.</li>
      <li>Motivate and utilize the individual strengths of team members.</li>
      <li>Express gratitude for team members&rsquo; contributions and time.</li>
      <li>Communicate effectively and thoroughly so that all team members understand what&rsquo;s going on.</li>
      <li>Ask for and listen to the different needs and viewpoints of your team members.</li>
      <li>Commit to the team and be reliable; don&rsquo;t overcommit and then slow the whole team down.</li>
      <li>Be flexible and innovative; in particular, be willing to adopt a flexible group hierarchy that can flatten under circumstances where you want everyone to contribute.<sup>18</sup></li>
      <li>Be open-minded and willing to listen to all team members, including those who tend to be overlooked.</li>
      <li>Spot, diagnose and defuse discord between team members early.<sup>18</sup></li>
    </ul>
  </div>
    
      <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-users"></i> <strong>11S4.</strong>  Identify external partners.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Stakeholders are those parties who have—or could have—a direct interest in an organization&rsquo;s programs. </p>
    <p>Organizations can have a variety of stakeholders. These could include:<sup>19</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Staff</li>
      <li>Those who directly benefit from an organization&rsquo;s programs</li>
      <li>Those who provide the services funded by those programs</li>
      <li>Clinical and health professionals and their organizations</li>
      <li>State programs and agencies</li>
      <li>Local health agencies</li>
      <li>Community-based organizations</li>
      <li>Agency leaders</li>
      <li>Political leaders</li>
      <li>Advocacy and voluntary agencies</li>
      <li>Business community</li>
      <li>Faith community</li>
      <li>Health care providers, including hospitals and community</li>
      <li>health centers</li>
      <li>Academic institutions</li>
    </ul>
    <p>To determine the extent of a stakeholder&rsquo;s engagement in the collaborative process:<sup>20</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Define their potential role in the process.</li>
      <li>Determine their level of knowledge of the issues involved (what are their specific areas of expertise?).</li>
      <li>Determine their level of commitment (will they support or oppose the activity? To what extent and why?).</li>
      <li>Determine their available resources (staff, volunteers, money, technology, information, influence).</li>
      <li>Define their constraints (limitations: need funds to participate, lack of personnel, political or other barriers).</li></ul></div>
    
         <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-cogs"></i> <strong>11S5.</strong>  Interpret situations systemically.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>When addressing a situation, avoid the temptation to jump in immediately and begin making changes. Complex issues generally do not arise in a linear fashion, with action A leading to action B, resulting in outcome C. Quick fixes frequently result in unintended consequences that ultimately reverse any immediate improvement in the situation.<sup>21</sup></p>
    <p>Interdependencies among elements in a system tend to be indirect, circular, and nonobvious. However, these are what largely determine system performance. </p>
    <p>To improve the performance of the whole, you must improve the relationships among the system&rsquo;s elements. But not every part of the system needs to be changed. You can achieve system change by identifying a few key interdependencies that have the greatest effect on the performance of the entire system (aka, leverage points) and changing them in a sustained, coordinated way over time.</p>
    <p>Use the &ldquo;iceberg model&rdquo; to dig below more obvious events and trends in order to clarify the system structures at the root cause of complex, chronic problems:<sup>22</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Think of a problematic situation as the tip of the iceberg. </li>
      <li>Look for trends or patterns in the situation. (Ask, &ldquo;What has been happening?&rdquo;)</li>
      <li>Then identify &ldquo;structures&rdquo; (such as policies and procedures) that could be generating the trend. (Look for the &ldquo;why.&rdquo;)</li>
      <li>Look for the mental models that underlie the structures. (These could be pressures, policies, power dynamics, perceptions, purpose.)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
         <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-paper-plane-o"></i> <strong>11S6.</strong>  Assess environment (with input) for evidence-based strategies.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p><strong>Goals </strong>define what a program is trying to accomplish. They are statements of intent.<sup>23</sup> </p>
    <p>To determine goals, ask:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>In the long run, what effect does this program hope to have on the community?</li>
      <li>What is the overall improvement the program wants to achieve?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Set goals based on the needs and concerns of the community, families, and affected individuals, rather than on what you think should happen or your organization&rsquo;s agenda.</p>
    <p>When writing goal statements, make them simple and concise, and include who will be affected and what will change as a result of the program.</p>
    <p><strong>Objectives </strong>support goals, but are more specific. They state how much of the goal will be accomplished within a certain timeframe, and define specific accomplishments or benchmarks that will demonstrate incremental progress toward the goal.<sup>23</sup></p>
    <p>There are three types of objectives:<sup>24</sup></p>
<ol>
  <li>Process objectives: These provide the groundwork or implementation necessary to achieve your other objectives.</li>
  <li>Behavioral objectives: These look at changing the behaviors of people (what they are doing and saying) and the products (or results) of their behaviors.</li>
  <li>Community-level outcome objectives: These are focused on change at the community level instead of an individual level.</li>
</ol>
    <p>When setting objectives, focus on outcomes. Objectives should follow the SMART rules, meaning they should be:<sup>25</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Specific (clear, concise, and understandable)</li>
      <li>Measurable</li>
      <li>Achievable</li>
      <li>Realistic</li>
      <li>Time-framed (with a specific date for accomplishment)    </li>
    </ul>
    <p>When writing out objectives, begin with a verb and state the objective in terms of results. <a href="https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/structure/strategic-planning/create-objectives/main">Read more about creating objectives</a>.</p>
    <p>To create a list of <strong>factors that facilitate or impede implementation of evidence-based/informed strategies</strong>, consider the following:<sup>26</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>What are stakeholder expectations? Are they vague, ambiguous or unreasonable?</li>
      <li>What complications might arise as a result of the complexity of a strategy?</li>
      <li>What level of experience with planning and implementing major changes do staff members have?</li>
      <li>Are there enough resources &mdash; funding, hours, attention, or personnel &mdash; to implement this strategy while maintaining other work?</li>
      <li>Are staff members confronting many significant issues and challenges at the same time? Are there multiple &ldquo;number-one&rdquo; priorities?</li>
      <li>Can we find a middle ground between implementing the change too quickly and having no pressure at all to get the change done?</li>
      <li>Does this strategy represent a major departure from prior practice?</li>
      <li>Does implementing this strategy require more and faster responsiveness than our organization is typically capable of?</li>
      <li>Have there been lots of changes in policies or personnel within this organization that may have caused organizational instability and change fatigue?</li>
      <li>What kind of relationship does our organization have with the community it serves? Is it positive or troubled?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Identifying the <strong>priority goals and objectives </strong>can be done in a variety of ways. Your group may be able to discuss and quickly come to consensus if there are a few things that emerge as clear priorities. A longer list requires a more formal decision-making process. Draw on the techniques reviewed in Competency 10. Multivoting may work well in such situations: Give each group member three to five colored stickers to use to identify their top priorities. Items that receive the most votes can then be placed higher on the list of priorities.<sup>27</sup></p>
    <p>If priorities are not easily agreed upon, a more formal approach may be necessary. A prioritization matrix is a simple tool that provides a way to sort a wide range of items 
      into an order of importance. It enables groups to see clearly which projects are the most important to focus on first.<sup>28</sup></p>
    <p>Part of the process of creating objectives is to create a <strong>timeline </strong>in which they will be accomplished.<sup>29</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Consider what is realistic to get accomplished in a certain time. </li>
      <li>Break down objectives into tasks, the specific steps needed to accomplish each objective. </li>
      <li>If possible, assign each task to someone appropriate.</li>
      <li>Keep in mind that timelines may change.</li></ul></div>     
    
  <p><em><strong>Advanced.</strong> Building on the foundational skills, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-calculator"></i> <strong>11S7.</strong> Manage projects effectively and efficiently.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>A project has these characteristics:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>A unique purpose</li>
      <li>Temporary</li>
      <li>Requires resources</li>
      <li>Developed using progressive elaboration</li>
      <li>Involves uncertainty</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Project management is a professional practice that applies knowledge, skills, tools and techniques to project activities to meet project requirements.<sup>31</sup></p>
    <p>There are five phases of a project:<sup>31</sup></p>
    <ol>
      <li>Initiation and Conception
        <ul>
          <li>Define the project at a broad level. </li>
          <li>Determine whether the project is feasible. If so, outline the purpose and requirements of the project.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Plan: 
        <ul>
          <li>Set goals for the projects (use the SMART method for defining these). </li>
          <li>Define the scope of the project: Clearly define the need for and benefits of the project, along with objectives, deliverables, and key milestones. </li>
          <li>Create the project plan: Identify the cost, resources available, and a realistic timetable. Establish baselines or performance measures using the project&rsquo;s scope, schedule and cost; baselines will help determine if the project is on track. Create a work breakdown schedule and assign roles. Use a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gantt_chart">Gantt chart</a> to visualize the project&rsquo;s timeline.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Execute
        <ul>
          <li>Develop the team/s, assign resources and execute the project plan, with team members carrying out the tasks assigned to them. </li>
          <li>Set up a tracking system. </li>
          <li>Update the project schedule as needed via status meetings.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Monitor and Control
        <ul>
          <li>Measure project progression and performance and that everything is going according to plan. </li>
          <li>Use key performance indicators (KPIs) to determine progress and performance. KPIs are typically five to seven indicators specific to the project that indicate progress. </li>
          <li>Adjust schedules and resources as needed to keep the project on track.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Close
        <ul>
          <li>Hold a post-mortem meeting to identify what went well in a project and what didn&rsquo;t.</li>
          <li>Create a project punch list of unfinished tasks and work with team members to complete them.</li>
          <li>Compile the final project budget and project report. Gather project documents and deliverables and store them appropriately.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      </ol>
    <p>Generally, project managers should manage a project and not do the work related to the project. This will require them to <strong>delegate</strong> work to others appropriately.</p>
    <p>Here are suggestions on what to delegate:<sup>32</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Routine tasks that are done daily, weekly or monthly</li>
      <li>Detail work that requires close attention but no special skill (for example, double-checking figures)</li>
      <li>Tasks that don't require your decision-making input</li>
      <li>Attendance at regular meetings where another individual could easily represent you and later provide you with a summary</li>
      <li>Information-gathering through books, reports, newspapers, magazines or the internet</li>
      <li>Tasks that another individual could do just as well as you can</li>
      <li>Work that will challenge employees and improve their skills</li>
      <li>Tasks that others can do better than you, either because they really enjoy the work or have special knowledge or expertise </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Not every task can be delegated however. Here are suggestions on what not to delegate:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Responsibility for helping develop your company's mission, goals and vision.</li>
      <li>Jobs that only you have the knowledge, expertise and authority to handle</li>
      <li>Tasks that have been specifically assigned to you by a higher authority within the organization</li>
      <li>Leadership responsibilities for which you are directly accountable</li>
      <li>Tasks that would allow unnecessary access to proprietary data or confidential information </li>
    </ul>
    <p>The concept of<strong> shared responsibility</strong> is important to the success of a project. When problems arise, shared responsibility is the idea that all stakeholders in a project contribute to that problem in some way, and therefore all must also be involved in finding a solution.<sup>33</sup></p>
    <p>Steps to sharing responsibility for a problem include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Ask each stakeholder to identify key challenges and concerns.</li>
      <li>Identify how these challenges are affecting the project.</li>
      <li>Ask stakeholders to describe what successful resolution of the problem would look like.</li>
      <li>Work together to come up with ways to reach that success point.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Staffing </strong>is another essential part of project management. As the word suggests, it involves assembling the appropriate people with the skills required for each role in the project.<sup>34</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>A first step in staffing is to define what skill sets will be needed to carry out the project.</li>
      <li>Reconcile the skill sets of existing staff members with those that will be required. This will help identify where temporary/contract staff might be needed.</li>
      <li>Map personnel to duties to create a staffing plan. Establish lines of communication, including who reports to whom.</li>
      <li>Provide regular feedback to staff, and continue to evaluate whether staffing needs are being met appropriately.    </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Evaluations </strong>provide an opportunity for in-depth reflection on the strategy and assumptions guiding the project. They assess progress made toward the achievement of a project&rsquo;s objectives and may recommend adjustments to its strategy. They are also a way to assess how well project-level actions link to and support an organization&rsquo;s higher level strategies and objectives.<sup>35</sup></p>
    <p>Establish a monitoring and evaluation system during the project design stage to gather information that can help partners and project managers to continuously learn and improve. </p>
    <p>Evaluation can achieve the following:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Provide an early warning that activities and processes need corrective action</li>
      <li>Create opportunities for project stakeholders to reflect critically on the project&rsquo;s direction and decide on improvements</li>
      <li>Build understanding, motivation and capacity among those involved in the project</li>
    </ul>
    Assess progress to enable an organization to meet reporting requirements.</div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-microscope"></i> <strong>11S8.</strong>  Use implementation science.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Using implementation science methods can increase the likelihood that the delivery of evidence-based interventions can be sustained. In addition, implementation science strategies can improve the efficiency and reduce the resources required in a new implementation.<sup>36</sup> Implementation strategies are &ldquo;methods or techniques used to enhance the adoption, implementation, sustainment, and scale-up of a program or practice.&rdquo;<sup>37</sup> </p>
    <p>There are two types of strategies:<sup>7</sup> </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Discrete strategies</strong> involve a single action or process used to enhance implementation (e.g., reminders, training workshops).</li>
      <li><strong>Multifaceted strategies</strong> combine multiple discrete strategies to address multiple factors.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Unfortunately, the research evidence for implementation strategies has not been conducted using a consistent taxonomy. There have been efforts to do so, most recently the <a href="https://implementationscience.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13012-015-0209-1#Sec1">Expert Recommendations for Implementing Change (ERIC) project</a>, which created a final compilation of 73 implementation strategies. </p>
    <p>To design effective implementation strategies to address a change that is needed:<sup>7</sup> </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Conduct a context assessment. </li>
      <li>Identify potential barriers and prioritize them.</li>
      <li>Match them with discrete or multifaceted strategies that address those barriers.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>There are several methods of choosing implementation strategies, each with its strengths and weaknesses:<sup>38</sup> </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Concept mapping</li>
      <li>Group model building</li>
      <li>Conjoint analysis</li>
      <li>Intervention mapping</li>
    </ul>
    <p><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4761530/">Read more about these four methods</a>.</p>
    <p>Using implementation science methods can increase the accuracy of real-world initiatives to put interventions into action.</p>
  </div>
    
    <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-checklist"></i> <strong>11S9.</strong> Develop proficiency in admin/policy/finance.</button>
  <div class="panel">
	  <p><strong>Program Administration Basics</strong></p>
	  <p><strong>Conduct a Comprehensive Needs Assessment</strong>: A needs assessment is the foundation of an effective maternal and child health program. Conducting a needs assessment involves:</p> 
	  <ul>
	    <li>Gathering and analyzing data on health indicators</li>
	  <li>Gathering demographic information</li>
	  <li>Understanding the community circumstances affecting health within the target community</li></ul>
	  
	<p>The goal is to identify specific health challenges, gaps in services, and barriers to care that the local population faces. This information guides program design, ensures that resources address the most pressing needs, and that interventions are tailored to the community.</p>
	  <p><strong>Implement Evidence-based Interventions</strong>: Implementing evidence-based interventions ensures program effectiveness and credibility. This approach involves selecting and adapting strategies, practices, and policies that have been proven effective through rigorous research and evaluation.</p> 
	  <p>Program administrators should stay current with the latest research in maternal and child health, consulting reputable sources such as peer-reviewed journals, government health agencies, and professional organizations.</p> 
	  <p>When implementing these interventions, it's important to consider how they can be adapted to fit local contexts while maintaining fidelity to the core components that make them effective. This approach not only improves outcomes but also helps justify program funding and support.</p>
	  <p><strong>Responsiveness to various backgrounds: </strong>Responsiveness to various backgrounds is essential for providing effective and respectful care in different communities. This requires a deep understanding of various beliefs, practices and values that influence health behaviors and attitudes towards health care.</p>
      <p>Program administrators should ensure that staff receive ongoing training on responsiveness to various backgrounds and that program materials and services are appropriate for different community contexts. This may involve collaborating with community leaders, hiring staff from different backgrounds, and regularly seeking feedback from program participants. Programs that are responsive to various backgrounds are more likely to be accepted by the community, leading to better engagement and improved health outcomes.</p>
	  <p><strong>Collaboration:</strong> Effective collaboration is key to maximizing resources and providing comprehensive care. Maternal and child health programs should actively seek partnerships with a wide range of stakeholders, including healthcare providers, schools, social services, community organizations, and government agencies. These partnerships can help create a more integrated system of care, reduce duplication of services, and address the multiple factors that influence maternal and child health.</p> 
	  <p>Collaboration can take many forms, from formal referral systems and joint programs to regular community health coalitions. By working together, organizations can leverage each other's strengths and create a more holistic approach to improving maternal and child health.</p>
	  <p><strong>Data-driven decision making</strong>: Incorporating data-driven decision-making into program administration ensures that resources are used effectively and that programs remain responsive to changing needs. This involves establishing robust systems for data collection, analysis, and reporting.</p> 
	  <p>Programs should track key performance indicators, health outcomes, and process measures. Regular data reviews can help identify trends, highlight areas for improvement, and demonstrate program impact. Invest in data management systems and staff training to ensure data quality and effective use. Share data with stakeholders, including funders and community members, to build trust and support for the program.</p>
	  <p><strong>Continuous quality improvement:</strong> Implementing an environment of continuous quality improvement (CQI) is crucial for maintaining program effectiveness over time. CQI involves regularly assessing program performance, identifying areas for improvement, and implementing changes based on data and feedback. This process should be ongoing and involve all levels of staff. By constantly striving to improve, programs can adapt to changing needs, incorporate new evidence, and maintain high standards of care.</p>
	  <p>Workforce development: Investing in workforce development is essential for maintaining high-quality maternal and child health programs. This includes providing ongoing training and education opportunities for staff at all levels. Training should cover not only technical skills related to maternal and child health but also soft skills such as communication, responsiveness to various backgrounds and leadership. </p>
	  <p><strong>Family-centered approach: </strong>This approach involves treating families as partners in care, respecting their values and choices, and empowering them with knowledge and resources to make informed decisions. Programs should be designed to accommodate the needs of entire families, including extended family members who may play important roles in childcare. This may involve offering flexible appointment times, providing child-friendly spaces in clinics, and developing educational materials that are accessible to all family members. </p>
	  <p><strong>Balanced health opportunities focus:</strong> Prioritizing balanced health opportunities involves not only ensuring available access to services but also actively working to address the community circumstances affecting health that contribute to variations. Programs should collect and analyze data organized by background factors, community factors, income, and other relevant information to identify and target variations. Support policies that promote balanced health opportunities at the local, state, and national levels.</p>
	  <p><strong>Sustainable funding</strong>: Developing sustainable funding strategies involves having several funding sources to reduce reliance on any single funder. Programs should explore a mix of government grants, private foundations, corporate sponsorships and individual donations. It's important to develop strong grant writing and fundraising capabilities within the organization. Programs should also focus on demonstrating their value and impact through rigorous evaluation and clear communication of outcomes to funders and stakeholders. Efficient resource allocation and cost-effective interventions are crucial for stretching limited budgets.</p>
	<p><strong>Understanding Health Care Policy Development</strong></p> 
	  <p>Health care for all individuals is shaped by access to quality, affordable health insurance. Three public insurance programs created and shaped by health care policies affect the financing of MCH: Medicaid, Children's Health Insurance Program, and the health insurance marketplaces offered through the Affordable Care Act. All three serve significant portions of the nation&rsquo;s women, children, and children and youth with special health care needs (CYSHCN). </p>
    <p>The Affordable Care Act was enacted in 2010 to provide a comprehensive national health policy. The ACA sought to improve access to health care by creating individual insurance markets and expanding access to Medicaid.<sup>40</sup> </p>
    <p>The ACA created marketplaces to serve different groups:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Individual insurance marketplaces allow eligible individuals and families to buy coverage. </li>
      <li>Small business insurance marketplaces help firms with 50 or fewer employees cover their workers.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Medicaid was created in 1965 to provide health coverage to certain low-income families.<sup>41</sup> It is funded jointly by the federal government and states. Each state operates its own Medicaid program within federal guidelines. Because these guidelines are broad, there can be significant variation in eligibility requirements and benefits from state to state. Medicaid serves mostly women, children, and CYSHCN. <a href="https://www.medicaid.gov/">More about Medicaid</a>.</p>
    <p>The Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) was created in 1997 as a public insurance program to cover uninsured children and, in some states, pregnant women, in families whose income exceeds the Medicaid eligibility requirements.41 States are given flexibility in how they implement CHIP programs. CHIP may be a Medicaid expansion program, its own freestanding program, or a combination of the two. <a href="https://www.medicaid.gov/chip/index.html">More about CHIP</a>.</p>
    <p><a href="https://academicguides.waldenu.edu/library/healthpolicy/govtwebsites">View a list of health care policy websites.</a></p>
	  
	<p><strong>Understanding Health Care Financing</strong></p> 
	<p>Financial realities play a role in most aspects of health care decision-making. As a result, an understanding of the fundamentals of health care finance is essential.</p>
    <p>Health care finance includes the accounting and financial management functions of health care organizations.<sup>39</sup> </p>
    <p>Though they are separate fields, accounting and financial management are interdependent. Accounting provides the data needed for good decision-making, and financial management offers the necessary structure (through theory, concepts, and tools) in which those decisions can be made.</p>
    <p>Activities involved with finance in health care organizations fall into one of the &ldquo;four C&rsquo;s.&rdquo; These are:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Cost</li>
      <li>Cash management</li>
      <li>Capital acquisition</li>
      <li>Control of resources</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Specific examples of these activities include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Estimating costs and profitability, planning and budgeting</li>
      <li>Managing financial operations</li>
      <li>Making financing decisions</li>
      <li>Making capital investment decisions</li>
      <li>Financial reporting</li>
      <li>Financial and operational analysis</li>
      <li>Contract management</li>
    </ul>
	  
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-wrench"></i> <strong>11S10.</strong> Recognize impact of past factors/grow external partnerships.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>The legacy of past factors continues to manifest as health variations in MCH outcomes. To build effective and sustainable partnerships that address these differences, it is essential to acknowledge and understand the root causes. This requires a deep commitment to openness, welcoming participation, and trust.</p>  
<p><strong>Understand the Impact of Past Factors</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Recognize community factors: Understand how past and ongoing community factors have  created and perpetuated variations in health care access, quality, and outcomes.</li>
<li>Empathize with practical knowledge: Listen to and validate the experiences of communities with specific needs, including their past and ongoing struggles.</li>
<li>Identify the consequences: Recognize how  certain factors have led to mistrust of health care systems, limited access to care, and varying health outcomes.</li></ul>
<p><strong>Build Trust through Openness and Welcoming Participation</strong></p>
<ul><li>Transparent communication: Establish open and honest communication channels with community partners, acknowledge past mistakes, and commit to transparency in decision-making.</li>
<li>Welcoming partnership development: Involve  communities with specific needs in partnership development, ensuring their voices are heard and respecting their expertise.</li>
<li>Responsiveness to various backgrounds: Demonstrate a commitment to learning about and understanding different ways of life and perspectives, avoiding stereotypes, and adapt practices accordingly.</li>
<li>Balanced influence considerations: Redistribute influence within partnerships to ensure balanced decision-making and resource allocation.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Foster Sustainable Partnerships</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Data-driven decision-making: Utilize data to identify variations in health outcomes and measure the impact of interventions, ensuring accountability and transparency.</li>
<li>Capability development: Invest in the capabilities of community partners to strengthen their ability to address health variations.</li>
<li>Long-term commitment: Build partnerships based on long-term commitment, rather than short-term projects, to create lasting change.</li>
<li>Evaluation and learning: Continuously evaluate partnership efforts, learning from successes and failures, and make necessary adjustments.</li></ul>

  
  </div>
    
     <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-wrench"></i> <strong>11S11.</strong> Build effective coalitions.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Building and maintaining a group of stakeholders who continue to be active and involved requires planning and effort on the part of MCH professionals.</p>
    <p>A coalition is an alliance of various organizations or individuals working towards the same goal. Coalitions (also called collaboratives, partnerships, and alliances) can be formal or informal, and may focus on a big goal related to a mission or a smaller, specific policy or programmatic goal.</p>
<p>An effective coalition can achieve more than any one organization could on its own by tapping into existing resources to create an approach that best fits the community. The coalition should be a sustainable endeavor to ensure that its impact will last into the future.</p>
<p>What follows are suggestions based on &ldquo;The Eight Steps to Effective Coalition Building,&rdquo; a framework developed by Larry Cohen, et al., for engaging individuals, organizations and governmental partners invested in addressing community concerns.<sup>42</sup></p>
<ol><li>Analyze program objectives and determine whether a coalition is needed. To begin this process, ask the following:
<ul><li>What are we trying to accomplish?</li>
<li>What are our strengths and needs?</li>
<li>What are the pros and cons associated with the proposed collaboration?</li>
<li>What are our objectives and what types of activities seem logical?</li></ul></li>
<li>Recruit the right people. The coalition&rsquo;s objectives will determine who should be invited to participate and how large or small the group can be. Remember: Smaller groups are more nimble, but larger groups can potentially access more resources.</li>
<li>Devise preliminary objectives and activities for the coalition. Early in the process, identify common goals and benefits that will come from cooperation. Put together a few efforts that will yield short-term outcomes to demonstrate the positives of the coalition.</li>
<li>Convene coalition members. This may happen as a standalone meeting or as part of a conference or workshop. The lead organizers of the coalition should prepare a strong proposal for the coalition&rsquo;s structure, including its mission and membership that they then open for comments on by those at the meeting. Do not expect every organization at this initial meeting to remain part of the coalition.</li>
<li>Anticipate the necessary resources. Develop a budget and map the resources that each coalition member organization can provide. The lead organizers should expect costs to be associated with organizing the coalition. However, the cost of achieving overall results should be less than if the lead organization attempted to accomplish these same objectives alone.</li>
<li>Develop a successful coalition structure. There are no rules governing how a coalition should be structured, but considering the following elements can help put a viable structure in place: how long will the coalition exist? Where will it meet? How frequently and for how long should it meet? How will decision making take place? Who will set meeting agendas? What membership rules will there be? What sort of participation between meetings by subcommittees or planning groups is to be expected?</li>
<li>Maintain coalition vitality by determining the following: how the coalition will acknowledge and address problems, how leadership will be shared, how new members will be recruited, and how training will be provided on needs that have been identified. Remember to celebrate the coalition’s successes.</li>
<li>Evaluate programs and improve as necessary. Ensure that every coalition program and activity is followed by an evaluation, and that feedback gathered is considered carefully.</li></ol>	  
<p><a href="https://www.preventioninstitute.org/publications/developing-effective-coalitions-an-eight-step-guide">Read more about effective coalition-building</a>.</p>
<p>To keep stakeholders engaged, be sure you understand:</p>
	  <ul><li>What is motivating the stakeholders to be a part of this group</li>
	  <li>How engagement strategies could vary across different types of stakeholders</li>
      <li>What restrictions (such as a funding source or regulations) exist for what you can offer to stakeholders to maintain engagement (e.g., payment, meals, continuing education credits)</li></ul>
<p>Strategies to keep stakeholders engaged:<sup>43</sup></p>
<ul><li>Whenever possible, establish reliable sources of funding to implement stakeholder recommendations, so that stakeholders have confidence that their time and efforts are worthwhile.</li>
<li>Offer additional training or education. This can also level the playing field for stakeholders of different backgrounds and experience levels.</li>
<li>Encourage the leader/s within a stakeholder group to reach out to group members individually to build and maintain personal connections with them.</li>
<li>Let stakeholders know how their input and the products of their work have made a difference, which will demonstrate the value of their work.</li>
<li>Provide benefits to active stakeholders, such as:
<ul><li>Information on grant opportunities</li>
<li>Ideas for grant proposals and letters of support
Time for networking with each other</li>
<li>Opportunities to hear from experts on a topic of shared interest to the stakeholder group</li>
<li>Opportunities to share concerns with local, state or federal leaders and other decision-makers</li></ul></li>
<li>Establish reciprocal support arrangements, such as an agreement to collaborate or at least to consider collaborating on initiatives of interest to individual stakeholders.</li>
<li>If permitted, provide stakeholders with some kind of financial support, such as covering membership dues to a relevant organization or providing a stipend (for example, for transportation or child care expenses)</li></ul>
<p>Careful planning and effective communication can help foster an environment of openness, welcoming participation, and trust among stakeholders:<sup>44, 45</sup></p>
<ul>
  <li>Actively recruit from the two areas of influence: those who have more influence (law enforcement, lawmakers, established organizations, etc.) and those who have less (new nonprofit groups, community members, youth, those with limited resources, those from various backgrounds). Acknowledge and address influence considerations and differences in resources. Manage the influence differences by being explicit about how decisions will be made and how resources will be used.</li>
  <li>Be clear about what you want to achieve by engaging stakeholders from various backgrounds. Avoid token representation.</li>
  <li>Incorporate various perspectives in how meetings are run. Ensure that meetings are welcoming to people from different backgrounds or who speak different languages.</li>
  <li>Consider different ways of engaging stakeholders other than having them join your coalition. Use key informant interviews or individual meetings to elicit input.</li>
  <li>Build trust by involving stakeholders in a respectful manner that responds to various backgrounds and communicating frequently and openly. Remember that trust takes time to build.</li>
</ul>
  </div>
    

     
     <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-town-hall"></i> <strong>11S12.</strong> Use community collaboration models.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Numerous models exist for those seeking to start the community collaboration process. Examples of these include:<sup>46</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Collective Impact: A process by which a group of key stakeholders from different sectors agree to a common agenda for solving a complex social problem at scale. Stakeholders agree to a common understanding of the problem and to take the same approach toward solving it. There&rsquo;s also a shared list of indicators to measure results over time. All stakeholders carry out the specific activities that they excel at, but in a way that is actively coordinated with others and therefore is mutually reinforcing. There is continuous communication among stakeholders, which builds trust. And there is a dedicated team that supports the overall effort, keeping participants focused on a common agenda, synthesizing and explaining data and keeping participants connected.<sup>47</sup></li>
      <li>PRECEDE/PROCEED: &ldquo;PRECEDE&rdquo; stands for Predisposing, Reinforcing, and Enabling Constructs in Educational/Environmental Diagnosis and Evaluation. These form the process that leads up to the intervention in question. &ldquo;PROCEED&rdquo; stands for Policy, Regulatory, and Organizational Constructs in Educational and Environmental Development, which describes how to carry out the intervention itself.</li>
      <li>Healthy Cities/Healthy Communities: A theoretical framework for a participatory process by which citizens can create healthy communities.</li>
      <li>The Institute of Medicine's Community Health Improvement Process (CHIP): A framework for building community health that specifies process, including performance monitoring, but expects the community to identify the issues to be addressed and the methods by which that will happen.</li>
      <li>Strategic Prevention Framework (SPF): A process that an organization, initiative, community, or state can follow in order to address a community issue affecting a given population group. It was developed to prevent and reduce the use and abuse of alcohol, tobacco, and drugs among youth, but can be adapted for use with other issues.</li>
      <li>Health Impact Assessment (HIA): A tool that helps community leaders, legislators, and others determine the health and safety impacts that their proposed projects may have on area residents and community members. It considers the social, economic, political and physical determinants of health.</li>
      <li>MAP-IT: A framework that helps a coalition plan and evaluate public health interventions in a community with the following steps: Mobilize, Assess, Plan, Implement, and Track.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>How to leverage existing efforts</strong>. Existing community improvement efforts offer MCH organizations the opportunity to establish new and innovative partnerships. Think critically about the resources you need and the organizations that may be able to provide those resources. Similarly, consider what you have to offer and list the organizations where your resources will be of the most benefit.<sup>48</sup></p>
    <p><strong>Find potential partners</strong>. 
      Reach out to information sources such as coalitions, community development corporations, local city officials or neighborhood associations to learn more about prevalent needs and/or targeted efforts within the community. This may be helpful in prioritizing where to begin partnership development. </p>
    <p>Another method of identifying potential partner organizations is to use a request for proposals (RFP). An RFP is a formal document that invites prospective partners to submit a proposal outlining their needs. Once you receive proposals from potential partners, use an objective process to review and rate them and select the best partners for your program.</p>
    <p><strong>Assess potential partners</strong>. 
      Once you have identified community organizations as potential partners, you need to evaluate those organizations to determine if they are a good fit for your program — and if your program is a good fit for them.</p>
    <p>Consider these important factors when assessing potential partners:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Type of organization: Is it the type of organization you want to partner with (e.g., nonprofit, school, local government, faith-based, neighborhood association, etc.)?</li>
      <li>Mission and organizational approach: Clearly understand the partner's mission and organizational approach. Are they a good fit with your organization? It is especially important to determine if both organizations have a shared goal of service in the community.</li>
      <li>Issue area: Does the organization work around the issue you want to address (youth, environment, education, etc.)?</li>
      <li>Resources: Determine if the partner can offer the types of resources your program needs. Also, ensure that the partner needs what you can offer.</li>
      <li>Location: Is the partner in a geographic area where your program currently serves or wants to expand?</li>
      <li>Policies and provisions: Review the provisions and policies that govern your program/organization to determine if this is an organization you can partner with.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Contact potential partners to assess partnership potential. This initial conversation between you and the community organization should be a fact-finding mission. Provide an overview of the services your program is able to offer. Keep the initial conversation brief; you are only trying to determine whether partnership opportunities are available.</p>
    <p><strong>Establish partnerships</strong>. 
      If an organization appears to meet the criteria of a potentially successful partner, the next step is to set up a meeting, either in person or virtually. </p>
    <p>One option for a face-to-face meeting is a site visit. A site visit is an opportunity to obtain a full understanding of the range of services the organization offers to the community and its clients. Visiting the site is a great way to assess potential opportunities for partnership by observing the facilities, clients, and various partnership possibilities. </p>
    <p>If the organization will be a good partner for your program, put a plan in place for developing projects with the partner. If no immediate action is necessary, but the partner has a great project possibility in the future, be sure to follow up.</p>
    <p><strong>Develop and support partnerships</strong>. 
      Developing partnerships to discover new projects or to strengthen your core offerings can be work. Approached correctly, however, partner relationships can be a critical element toward achieving success. Like any good relationship, a community partnership requires careful and intentional support to succeed. </p>
    <p>Suggestions for cultivating successful partnerships:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Maintain open and honest communication</li>
      <li>Make and take every opportunity to build a strong, trusting relationship with your partner</li>
      <li>Create and keep a shared vision</li>
      <li>Create ownership among partners</li>
      <li>Seek common ground and act</li>
      <li>Stop occasionally to evaluate</li>
      <li>Be patient </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Establish partnership parameters</strong>. 
      As partnerships and project ideas develop, both parties should establish parameters for the relationship. Parameters should serve as general guidelines and outline the requirements of each partner&rsquo;s contribution. </p>
    <p><strong>Formalize the partnership</strong>. 
      Key staff from both organizations should sit down, discuss, and clarify their understanding of the roles and responsibilities in the partnership. Together, they should develop written documents, such as a memorandum of understanding (MOU), to outline the partnership agreement.</p>
    <p><strong>Continue support</strong>. 
      Throughout the partnership, continue to work with and support your partner organization. Be sensitive to potential needs, changes, challenges, or other opportunities to adapt and strengthen your relationship. Ensure that both partners understand the other's programs, missions, and objectives, and that they can articulate these things to the community. Don't forget to recognize and celebrate the partner's contributions and achievements.</p>
    <p><a href="https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/implement/improving-services/coordination-cooperation-collaboration/main">Read more about Promoting Coordination, Cooperative Agreements, and Collaborative Agreements Among Agencies</a>.</p>
  </div>
    
  
